ess}0{\textperiodcentered}0001). Patients allocated 5-aminolevulinic acid had higher 6-month progression free survival than did those allocated white light (41{\textperiodcentered}0{\%} [32{\textperiodcentered}8-49{\textperiodcentered}2] vs 21{\textperiodcentered}1{\%} [14{\textperiodcentered}0-28{\textperiodcentered}2]; difference between groups 19{\textperiodcentered}9{\%} [9{\textperiodcentered}1-30{\textperiodcentered}7], p=0{\textperiodcentered}0003, Z test). Groups did not differ in the frequency of severe adverse events or adverse events in any organ system class reported within 7 days after surgery. Interpretation: Tumour fluorescence derived from 5-aminolevulinic acid enables more complete resections of contrast-enhancing tumour, leading to improved progression-free survival in patients with malignant glioma. {\textcopyright} 2006 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.},
